%h2
  Autoconf

%p
  If your ruby (usually 1.9.2-head / trunk) fails to compile and the make error log shows
  that you do not have a current enough version of autoconf ::cough:: CentOS ::cough:: then
  you can install it into your RVM.
%pre.code
  :preserve
    ∴ rvm package install autoconf
    
%p
  Once autoconf has been installed, you can then (re) install your ruby cleanly
%pre.code
  :preserve
    ∴ rvm remove 1.9.2-head
    ∴ rvm install 1.9.2-head -C --with-autoconf-dir=$rvm_path/usr
